ABSTRACT
Data storytelling (DS) is rapidly gaining attention as an approach
that integrates data, visuals, and narratives to create data stories that
can help a particular audience to comprehend the key messages un-
derscored by the data with enhanced eciency and eectiveness. It
is been posited that DS can be especially advantageous for audiences
with limited visualisation literacy, by presenting the data clearly
and concisely. However, empirical studies conrming whether data
stories indeed provide these benets over conventional data vi-
sualisations are scarce. To bridge this gap, we conducted a study
with 103 participants to determine whether DS indeed improve
both eciency and eectiveness in tasks related to information re-
trieval and insights comprehension. Our ndings suggest that data
stories do improve the eciency of comprehension tasks, as well
as the eectiveness of comprehension tasks that involve a single
insight, compared with conventional visualisations. Interestingly,
these benets were not associated with participants visualisation
literacy.

1 INTRODUCTION
The critical role that data plays, and is anticipated to continue
playing, in our society is evident through the progressively deeper
integration of data-driven decision-making and advanced analytics
across various sectors, such as healthcare [
90
], manufacturing [
70
],
education [
97
], nance [
83
], and more. As a result, eective data
visualisation has become pivotal in supporting the exploration, anal-
ysis, and interpretation of these abundant data [
31
,
59
]. However,
not all data visualisations are created with the same intent. Some
visualisations are tailored for experts with in-depth knowledge
of data analysis. For instance, business analysts might use such
visualisations to enhance marketing strategies through a detailed
market analysis [
20
]. These visualisations are often referred to as
exploratory visualisations and are primarily aimed at users with
expertise in data analysis who are exploring and seeking insights
from unfamiliar datasets [14, 43, 50, 62].
In contrast, some visualisations are designed to present informa-
tion to a broader audience, who may not be familiar with specic
visualisation techniques but still need to understand the key insights
derived from the data [
9
,
55
]. For instance, journalists frequently
use data visualisations to help the general public understand com-
plex topics such as climate change [
3
]. Teachers are beginning
to employ learning analytics visualisations to gain insights into
and enhance their students performance [
25
], while individuals
often turn to tness app visualisations to track their health status
[
95
]. Such visualisations have an explanatory objective, focusing
on presenting and communicating insights rather than inviting
people to explore the data [
26
,
43
,
50
,
79
]. These explanatory visu-
alisations can be used in various contexts, from illustrating body
weight trends in a tness app [e.g.
66
] to showcasing uctuating
indicators within a company for informed decision-making [e.g.
20
].
However, previous empirical studies have shown that the general
CHI 24, May 1116, 2024, Honolulu, HI, USA Shao, et al.
public often possesses a relatively low level of visualisation literacy,
meaning they frequently struggle to condently interpret visual
representations of data [8, 23, 55, 61].
In this context, data storytelling is gaining prominence for help-
ing people grasp key insights from the data [
84
]. Data storytelling
has been dened as "a structured approach for communicating data
insights more eectively to an audience using narrative elements and
data visualisations" (p. 299) [
24
, p.299]. While conventional visuali-
sations are often designed to engage the audience in an exploration
of the data presented [
77
], their ability to explain or communicate
data insights can be further enhanced by incorporating data story-
telling elements [
99
]. These elements emphasise specic messages
in the data, for example, by adding text explanations for trends or
outliers [
27
,
75
], and by highlighting the results of the analysis in
titles [
48
] and text annotations [
89
]. This approach also involves
reducing the emphasis on less relevant visualisation elements and
data points [4, 47, 85].
Various authors have suggested that data storytelling can help
in communicating key insights more eectively [
20
,
37
,
47
,
51
,
85
]
and more eciently [
81
,
100
102
] compared to conventional vi-
sualisation. The premise is that this is achieved by reducing the
complexity of the information and focusing only on essential data
and visual elements. Moreover, the addition of data storytelling
elements to conventional visualisations to create data stories has
been seen as a potential bridge to close the comprehension gap by
audiences with limited data knowledge or data visualisation liter-
acy [
26
,
54
,
60
]. Yet, there is limited empirical evidence to back the
proposed advantages of data storytelling elements in the existing
literature. While some studies have explored the potential benets
of data storytelling over conventional visualisations in areas like
engagement [
10
,
103
], empathy [
11
,
58
,
64
], and memory recall [
99
],
the results have been mixed. A signicant gap remains in empirical
studies that address the central premise driving the adoption of
data storytelling in data visualisation: does it actually assist people
in more eectively and eciently discerning and understanding
critical data insights compared to conventional visualisations? Ad-
ditionally, some preliminary research has examined the potential
correlation between audience preferences and personality traits,
and data storytelling [
98
]. However, no study has delved into how
an individuals visualisation literacy might inuence the overall
eectiveness and eciency of data storytelling.
The primary contribution of this paper is the empirical evidence
it provides through a comparative study. This study evaluated
whether visualisations with data storytelling elements improves
eciency (measured by the time taken) and eectiveness (mea-
sured by accuracy rates), in two specic tasks: information retrieval
(which involves pinpointing key data points) and data compre-
hension (which entails understanding main insights). Compared
against conventional visualisations, these ndings can oer action-
able insights for visualisation designers, enabling them to make
evidence-based decisions on whether to employ data storytelling
elements or stick with conventional visualisations for specic tasks,
eectively bridging a notable gap in the existing literature. A total
of 103 participants, with varied data visualisation experience, visu-
alisation literacy and backgrounds, participated in the study where
they were asked to identify relevant data points and key insight(s)
from a set of 6 visualisations 3 of which were conventional and
the other 3 integrated data storytelling elements. We also assessed
participant perceptions of how specic data storytelling elements
might inuence task completion success rates. Furthermore, we
examined the relationship between an individuals visualisation
literacy and the eectiveness of data storytelling.
2 BACKGROUND AND RELATED WORK
Three areas are relevant to this paper: the theoretical foundations
of data storytelling, empirical studies that evaluate its purported
benets, and the role of visualisation literacy.
2.1 Foundations of Data Storytelling in Data
Visualisation
Conventional data visualisations primarily focus on presenting raw
data in a structured and, ideally, visually appealing manner [
92
].
These visualisations such as bar charts, line charts, pie charts,
scatter plots, heatmaps, area charts, and bubble charts are often
intended to serve as tools for users to explore and interpret the data
independently [
77
], offering the advantage of providing a snapshot
of the data and laying out facts in a way that can be visually in-
spected [
40
]. Yet, while conventional visualisations can be valuable,
they can sometimes fall short in conveying the deeper narrative
behind the data, specially for audiences with little expertise in data
analysis [
8
,
14
,
43
,
61
,
62
]. Understanding the story behind the data
is crucial for gaining meaningful insights and comprehending what
the data points or trends in a data visualisation represent in the
real world [
50
]. Data storytelling is argued to effectively bridge this
gap.
Storytelling is the act of weaving facts, insights, emotions and
intentions into a narrative that engages audiences and imbues
mean-
ing into complex ideas [
7
,
33
], often prompting action [
22
].
Apply-
ing this denition to the realm of data visualisation, data
storytelling
can be broadly described as the craft of transforming
raw numbers
and low-level data points into a cohesive narrative,
rendering data
not just understandable but actionable. This idea
is far from new.
Kosara and MacKinlay
[50]
identied that the
early attempts, that
resemble todays data storytelling practices,
can be traced back to
the 18th and 19th centuries when early
practitioners of statistics and
data analysis demonstrated the
power of visually presenting data
to show, explain or emphasise
the magnitude of certain problems
for numerically illiterate
decision-makers or general audiences. For example, early data
stories aimed to explain the scope of infectious
outbreaks after
careful analysis [
45
], present events in a digestible
format for
educational and training purposes [
37
], or advocate for
social
changes [18].
In the early 21st century, journalists, equipped with new tech-
nologies that made it more accessible to collect, analyse and vi-
sualise data, started to use numerical data to support narrative
storytelling in various news outlets [
85
,
88
]. As time progressed,
professionals across various industries have begun to recognise the
importance of communicating data-driven insights in an accessi-
ble and compelling manner [
20
,
76
]. Pioneers in the eld of data
visualisation, such as Edward Tufte, also emphasised the impor-
tance of contextualising data and providing a narrative structure
for better comprehension of what the numbers presented in a graph
actually mean [
92
]. In the last few years, several guides on how
Data Storytelling in Data Visualisation CHI 24, May 1116, 2024, Honolulu, HI, USA
to do data storytelling have started to emerge [
28
,
47
,
82
] making
this notion even more attractive and accessible to practitioners
across several industries. Nowadays, data storytelling is being used
in a wide range of areas such as sports analytics [
35
,
104
], ed-
ucation [
62
,
93
], psychology [
53
], social work [
96
] and heritage
transmission [
86
]. In short, both early and contemporary data sto-
rytelling eorts have primarily focused on presenting ndings to a
broader audience interested in the insights, rather than in the data
analysis itself. However, it is only very recently that the concept
of data storytelling has begun to be more formally dened and
examined.
Segel and Heer
[85]
were pioneers in establishing the design
space of narrative visualisations as a foundation for data story-
telling. They described how narrative elements could be integrated
with graphics and interaction techniques to organise data for the
purpose of conveying a specic message. Kosara and MacKinlay
[50]
further claried the term data storytelling, arguing that while
conventional data visualisation tools can facilitate data analysis, the
emphasis of data storytelling is on presenting insights derived from
such analysis. To this end, visual cues can be strategically employed
to prioritise certain interpretations over others [
42
]. These cues
may include titles [
48
,
89
] and graphical or textual annotations
[
27
,
52
,
65
,
74
] that augment existing conventional visualisation
components for added clarity or detail or to help guide the reader
to understand the data.
Based on this basic premise, various frameworks for data sto-
rytelling have emerged. For example, Bach et al
. [4]
suggested
a set of patterns that could help designers create data stories or
analyse the narratives of existing data stories. These patterns are
organised into ve groups each contributing to the augmentation,
ow, framing, emotion and engagement of the data story. Ojo
and Heravi
[69]
extracted data storytelling patterns from award-
winning journalistic data stories, identifying the most common
goals of data stories that can be encountered in the media (i.e.,
to inform, explain, persuade or entertain) and the data visualisa-
tion tools that provide the exibility required for incorporating
storytelling elements. Zhang et al
. [102]
introduced a conceptual
workow demonstrating how raw data or conventional data visu-
alisations could be transformed into data stories that emphasise
specic elements. Echeverria et al
. [25]
presented a model and im-
plementation for automating the creation of data stories based on
pre-set parameters by end-users. These advancements indicate a
growing interest in formalising the design characteristics of data
storytelling.
Despite the identication of numerous patterns and design ele-
ments in academic literature, most current data storytelling studies
converge on a limited set of key principles for data storytelling,
irrespective of the diverse ways it can be implemented. Echeverria
et al
. [25]
synthesised ve principles for transitioning from conven-
tional visualisations to data stories that i) direct the users attention
to ensure visual guidance, and ii) facilitate the narrative to deliver
the intended message or data insight(s) [
99
]. These principles are
based on the work of Ryan
[81]
and Knaic
[47]
, and they align
with the process proposed in the data storytelling framework by
Zdanovic et al
. [99]
which we use in this paper to enhance con-
ventional visualisations with data storytelling elements (details are
provided in the next section):
Principle #1 Identifying an explicit goal: This involves
understanding the audience, their level of technological savvi-
ness, and subject matter expertise, a common theme across
data storytelling literature [4, 24, 54, 85].
Principle #2 Removing redundant elements: This in-
volves eliminating elements that oer no additional value,
such as unnecessary data labels, markers, grids, legends,
tick marks, and axis labels. This principle is foundational in
eective data visualisation [
92
] and is emphasised in data
storytelling guides as a crucial decluttering step [
28
,
47
,
82
].
Principle #3 Employing storytelling elements with
discernment: This is, using annotations and visual cues
judiciously to clarify or to group related data. Yet, an excess
of annotations can clutter the visualisation and distract the
audience [
49
], potentially counteracting the goal of steering
attention [46].
Principle #4 Capturing interest: This involves minimis-
ing irrelevant visual elements (i.e., declutter) while empha-
sising crucial components, for example, by using colours or
bold/thick elements for highlights [28, 47].
Principle #5 Calling for action: This involves creating a
coherent and succinct visualisation that conveys the essential
narrative, for example, by guiding users toward the intended
action through an explicit title derived from the data [
4
,
69
].
2.2 Benets of Data Storytelling
Various authors have suggested that visualisations that contain
data storytelling elements, commonly referred to as data stories,
can help in communicating key insights more eectively. For in-
stance, Segel and Heer
[85]
posited that integrating narratives with
graphics oers a richer medium for communicating analysis re-
sults than merely using regular graphical tools for data analysis.
Similarly, Gershon and Page
[37]
argued that incorporating story-
telling elements into conventional data visualisations can contribute
to the communication of information eectively and intuitively.
Daradkeh
[20]
extended this argument, suggesting that such an
approach can lead to improved decision-making and business per-
formance. Authors like Knaic
[47]
and Krum
[51]
have explained
that visualisations enhanced with data storytelling elements oer
an advantage in that they leverage humans ecient perceptual
skills for visual pattern recognition. Indeed, the concept of pre-
attentive processing which is the subconscious stage that enables
people to quickly identify visual elements like colour, shape, and
orientation has provided foundational principles for the eld of in-
formation visualisation design [
40
]. Additionally, other researchers
[
81
,
100
102
] have highlighted data storytellings potential for ef-
cient communication. They argue that visualisations enhanced
with data storytelling elements can outperform conventional vi-
sualisation techniques when the design concentrates exclusively
on essential data and visual elements, thereby reducing complexity
and, consequently, shortening the time needed to comprehend the
data.
Despite the above claims in the literature, empirical evidence sup-
porting the relative eectiveness and eciency of data storytelling
over conventional visualisations remains limited. Some research
has empirical examined other potential advantages; for example,
CHI 24, May 1116, 2024, Honolulu, HI, USA Shao, et al.
Zhao et al
. [103]
found that caption-enriched visualisations are
more engaging and easier to use than those without. Similarly,
the qualitative analysis from the same study suggested that en-
hancements in data storytelling aid focus and memory. However,
a controlled study by Zdanovic et al
. [99]
found no signicant im-
pact of visualisations enhanced with data storytelling elements on
either short-term or long-term memory recall when compared to
conventional visualisations.
Mixed results also emerged in studies investigating data story-
tellings potential for fostering empathy or inuencing audience
attitudes. For instance, controlled studies by Boy et al
. [11]
and
Morais et al
. [64]
did not nd evidence supporting the idea that
adding anthropomorphic elements to visualisations enhances em-
pathy. Likewise, Liem et al
. [58]
found no signicant dierence in
empathetic responses between data stories using personal narra-
tives and conventional exploratory visualisations.
An important gap remains unaddressed in the literature: it is
unclear whether adding data storytelling elements to conventional
visualisations aid in the eective and ecient identication of
insights and corresponding critical data points when compared to
conventional visualisations. While small-scale eye-tracking studies
[
21
,
26
,
72
] suggest that data storytelling elements can attract users
attention, they do not directly examine whether such elements
facilitate better or faster comprehension of the data.
2.3 Visualisation Literacy
The purpose and message of a data visualisation may not always
be easily and accurately understood, even if the visualisation is
well-designed [
23
]. As mentioned above, initial attempts at data
storytelling aimed to bridge this comprehension gap for audiences
unfamiliar with data and visualisations [
50
]. Today, data storytelling
often targets groups without formal training in data or visualisation,
such as teachers [
72
], healthcare practitioners [
29
], and the general
public [
60
]. The construct that encapsulates the skills needed to
eectively interact with data visualisations is termed "visualisation
literacy" (VL) [56].
Visualisation literacy refers to the ability to accurately interpret
visual representations of data and to eciently and condently
extract, process, and draw conclusions from such visualisations
[
12
,
32
]. Intriguingly, multiple studies have shown that the general
public often struggles with interpreting visual data representations,
indicating a widespread low level of VL [
8
,
23
,
55
,
61
]. For instance,
a study by Maltese et al
. [61]
involving higher education students
revealed that most had diculty understanding even basic data visu-
alisations, such as simple bar charts. Brner et al
. [17]
found similar
results in a study involving museum attendees. Likewise, many
teachers nd it challenging to interpret educational dashboards,
primarily due to a lack of relevant data skills [68].
When evaluating the eectiveness and eciency of data stories,
it is crucial to consider the potential impact of an individuals level
of VL. To date, the only study that has examined the intersection
of VL and data storytelling is by Pozdniakov et al
. [73]
. This small-
scale eye-tracking study involved 23 teachers with varying levels
of VL who were tasked with reviewing visualisations presented in
dashboards. Some were enriched with data storytelling elements
(i.e., emphasis on certain data points) while others maintained a
control version containing conventional visualisations. The authors
found that teachers with lower VL levels potentially benet the
most from data storytelling enhancements in terms of reduced
cognitive load. Yet, the relationship between individual visualisation
literacy levels and the potential benets of data storytelling in
supporting eective and ecient insight identication remains
largely unexplored.
2.4 Contribution to HCI and Research
Questions
To address the gaps identied in the existing literature, this pa-
per presents a study aimed at providing empirical evidence on the
eciency and eectiveness of data storytelling compared to con-
ventional visualisations. Specically, we aimed to quantitatively
investigate whether visualisations enhanced with data storytelling
elements reduce the time required to answer questions based on
visualisations and improve accuracy in tasks related to information
retrieval (i.e., identifying key data points that support a given in-
sight) and comprehension (i.e., understanding the actual insight
or insights). Additionally, we qualitatively examined participants
perceptions regarding the helpfulness of data storytelling elements
to potentially elucidate the quantitative results. Finally, we assessed
the inuence of individuals visualisation literacy on the eective-
ness of data storytelling elements. As a result, we proposed the
following research questions:
RQ1: To what extent does data stories assist individuals in
discerning and understanding critical data insights more e-
ciently compared to conventional visualisations?
RQ2: To what extent does data stories assist individuals in
discerning and understanding critical data insights more ef-
fectively compared to conventional visualisations?
RQ3: To what extent do the potential improvements in e-
ciency and eectiveness oered by data storytelling elements
vary between information retrieval and comprehension
tasks?
RQ4: What are participants perceptions on the helpfulness of
data storytelling elements (e.g., annotations, visual high-
lights, and titles see details in the next section)?
RQ5: To what extent do the relationships between individ-
uals visualisation literacy and their task eciency and
eectiveness vary between data storytelling and conventional
visualisation conditions?
3 METHOD
This section presents the studys components, covering: i) the data
storytelling design elements, ii) dataset and materials used, iii) the
study procedure, iv) the participants, and v) the analysis.
3.1 Data Storytelling Design Elements and
Transformation Process
To reliably compare conventional visualisations with data stories
those enhanced with data storytelling elements we rst needed
to clearly identify these data storytelling elements. To maintain
alignment with prior research evaluating visualisations enhanced
CHI 24, May 1116, 2024, Honolulu, HI, USA
Data Storytelling in Data Visualisation
with data storytelling elements, we established a set of design ac-
tions that involve adding or eliminating visual design elements
to and from conventional visualisations to transform them into a
data story. In doing so, we built on the framework for data story-
telling proposed by Zdanovic et al
. [99]
, which is itself grounded in
the data storytelling principles put forth by Echeverria et al
. [25]
,
Ryan
[81]
, and Knaic
[47]
as introduced in Section 2.1. Zdanovic
et al
. [99]
describe a three-phase process comprising i) initially
exploring the data to nd the insight(s) to be communicated, ii)
crafting the visualisation, and iii) telling the story. The creation of
a conventional visualisation typically involves phases i) and ii). In
contrast, creating a data story entails considering the following data
storytelling elements in the order presented below, particularly in
phases ii) and iii). Notably, we excluded interactive elements from
our study to prevent the design decisions from being complicated
by confounding variables and to ensure consistency with previous
data storytelling evaluations [
11
,
64
,
99
,
103
]. Once the insights are
identied, we considered the following data storytelling design ele-
ments and concrete design actions for crafting the data stories from
conventional visualisations, adhering to the principles introduced
in Section 2.1, and are as follows:
1 Using the right visualisation technique according to
the storytelling goal (in phase ii principle #1, in Section 2.1).
Selecting the appropriate visualisation technique, such as a bar chart
or scatter plot, according to the data communication goal is crucial
for eectively conveying the relevant data insight(s) and setting
the stage for a compelling story [
30
,
92
]. Adhering to Knaics [
47
]
recommendations, effective data storytelling may, although not
always necessary, involve changing chart types to better convey
the narrative. For example, to highlight temporal trends, switching
from pie charts to a line chart can be more illustrative, as shown in
Figure 1.
2 Eliminating clutter (in phase ii principles #2 & #3). Re-
ducing extraneous visual elements can make a visualisation more
easily interpretable, allowing viewers to focus only on key elements
[
39
,
92
]. While this is a principle that is also generally applicable to
any conventional data visualisation (i.e., reducing the data-ink ratio
[
92
]), it becomes vital in data storytelling to allow other visual ele-
ments to stand out and eectively draw attention. This is illustrated
in Figure 1 (right) by minimising axis information, removing details
for less relevant data points, labelling data series directly instead
of using legends, and using minimal colour variation. Importantly,
decluttering can also be applied to the excessive use of annotations
and other data storytelling elements (see below).
3 Directing attention by emphasising data points and
trends (in phase iii see principle #4). For the specic case of data
stories, the counterpart to decluttering is adding emphasis. This
can be achieved through techniques like employing contrasting
colours, highlighting specic data points, or making certain trend
lines bolder. These techniques aid in directing the viewers attention
towards crucial data points and trends associated with the main
insights identied in phase i, enabling them to comprehend the
story being conveyed [
47
]. Ware
[94]
explained how using colour
could guide the viewers attention, while Few
[30]
emphasised the
importance of eectively using visual hierarchy to direct attention.
For instance, in Figure 1 (right), this is illustrated by emphasising
the data series corresponding to strawberry revenue with a thick,
coloured line, including details/annotations for relevant data points
(A), and consistently using the same colour in the text, lines and
other parts of the visualisation to refer to these data points (B).
4 Adding annotations (in phase iii principles #3 & #4).
Annotations provide contextual or explanatory information directly
on the visualisation, helping to clarify or further emphasise key
points and trends [
42
,
89
]. As previously mentioned, annotations
can be graphical or textual. In our study, following Knaic
[47]
s
recommendations, we mainly utilised textual annotations for two
purposes: to explain data points or trends that are relevant to the
insight(s) identied in phase i, and to convey insights in straightfor-
ward language. An example of this is depicted in Figure 1 (right-C),
which demonstrates how the narrative succinctly explains the pri-
mary insight the tripling of strawberry sales revenue using
plain language for clarity.
5 Adding an explanatory title (in phase iii principle #5). A
well-crafted title not only describes the visualisation but also guides
the viewer towards the intended conclusion or call to action, serv-
ing as a headline for the data story. Knaic
[47]
recommends adding
a prescriptive title that summarises key ndings or even suggests a
course of action as a powerful element in data storytelling. Pozd-
niakov et al
. [72]
and Kong et al
. [48]
demonstrated that adding a
title on top of each chart drives attention and can potentially guide
interpretation. An example of a title that briey summarises a key
insight is shown in Figure 1 (right-D). In our study, we added an

We conducted two pilot studies before rolling out the full study,
involving three university students to ne-tune the survey, with
the second pilots data being incorporated (2 participants). Partici-
pants were allowed to skip up to three questions but skipping more

The participants came from six dierent regions, with the major-
ity coming from North America/Central America (39), Europe (34),
and Africa (22). The remainder were from South America (4), Ocea-
nia (3), and Asia (1). They identied as female (42), male (60), and

students at the time of the survey. Examining the participants elds
of employment, a signicant portion worked in the Technology and
IT sector (12), pursued by roles in sales, retail, and customer service
(7), and administration and management (6). Seven participants
were actively seeking employment or were currently unemployed.
A few were job-seeking (7) or represented other sectors, including
healthcare and engineering.
Around a third of participants (32) engaged in data analysis in
their jobs. About half (51) had a basic understanding of the concept,
while 30 were only familiar with the term. A small group had
substantial knowledge (15) or professional expertise (3), whereas
4 had no exposure to the domain. Concerning data visualization,
most encountered it through newspapers, apps, and websites (48),
and in their professional roles (36), although just a few considered
themselves professionals in this eld (5). This means that, overall,
most participants lacked expertise in data analysis and visualization.

4 RESULTS
4.1 Preliminary Exploration
Before examining our research questions, we conducted a prelimi-
nary analysis of participants responses. On average, participants
completed the study in 40.7 minutes (std. dev.= 8.4). To nd out
if comprehension questions took longer to answer than informa-
tion retrieval questions, we used Mann-Whitney tests. This analy-
sis revealed that comprehension questions took longer to answer
(median: 37.497 seconds, IQR: 17.279) than information retrieval
questions (median: 28.043 seconds, IQR: 13.948). This dierence
was statistically signicant and had a moderate eect size (U = 4423,
Z = 4.036, p < 0.0001, r = 0.281). This is consistent with Blooms
Taxonomy, where Level 1 questions are typically simple, and Level
2 questions demand in-depth understanding.
Further breaking down the comprehension questions, we saw
that questions seeking multiple insights took more time (median:
44.572 seconds, IQR: 31.587) than those asking for a single insight
(median: 28.392 seconds, IQR: 15.828) or information retrieval ques-
tions. These dierences were statistically signicant and both had
a large eect size (U = 4833, Z = 6.85, p < 0.0001, r = 0.477; U = 4960,
Z = 6.685, p < 0.0001, r = 0.466). However, there was not a notable
dierence in the time taken to respond to information retrieval
questions compared to single insight comprehension questions.
This trend conrms that questions requiring multiple insights natu-
rally take more time to answer compared to the ones focusing on a
single insight, which took roughly the same time as the information
retrieval questions.
Our analysis revealed that participants correctly answered com-
prehension questions less frequently (median: 0.556, IQR: 0.334)
compared to information retrieval questions (median: 0.778, IQR:
0.333). This dierence was substantial and signicant with a mod-
erate eect size (U = 231, Z = -5.87, p < 0.0001, r = 0.409). When we
separated the comprehension questions into dierent sub-types for
a more detailed analysis, we observed that questions that sought
multiple insights had a lower success rate (median: 0.556, IQR: 0.445)
compared to questions that aimed for a single insight (median: 0.778,
IQR: 0.444). This nding was also statistically signicant and ex-
hibited a moderate eect size (U = 523.5, Z = -4.788, p < 0.0001, r =
0.334). However, there was no notable dierence in the success rates
of information retrieval questions and single insight comprehen-
sion questions. This demonstrates that comprehension questions
requiring multiple insights were notably more challenging than the
other types, which aligns with our expectations.
We also analysed the potential impact of changing chart types
(see Table 1) using Mann-Whitney tests. Our exploration found
that the average success time difference between data storytelling
and conventional visualisations with chart type changes (median:
-0.087 seconds, IQR: 17.682) was not significantly different from that
without chart type changes (median: -0.332 seconds, IQR: 15.128)
(U = 2097, Z = -0.737, p = 0.4625, r = 0.051). Similarly, the correct
rate difference between data storytelling and conventional visu-
alisations with chart type changes (median: -0.087 seconds, IQR:
17.682) was not significantly different from that without chart type
changes (median: 0.167, IQR: 0.417) (U = 2240, Z = -0.152, p = 0.8801,
r = 0.011). These ndings indicate that altering the chart type when
converting traditional visualisations to data storytelling did not sig-
nificantly affect the efciency or efficiency of the visualisations.
The next subsections delve into the analysis comparing data
storytelling with conventional visualisations.
4.2 RQ1 - Data Storytelling and the Ecient
Communication of Insights
First, we explored whether data storytelling indeed assisted the
participants in discerning and understanding critical data insights
more eciently compared to conventional visualisations. Contrary
to expectations that data storytelling could enhance the eciency
of communicating insights, our ndings indicate no signicant dif-
ference (U = 2505, Z = 0.195, p = 0.8465, r = 0.014) in the metric
of average success time between data storytelling (median: 34.618
seconds, IQR: 16.599) and conventional data visualisation (median:
32.625 seconds, IQR: 15.548), when considering all the tasks pre-
sented to the participants as a whole (see Figure 4).
These results suggest that conventional visualisation methods
hold their ground in terms of eciency, opening up an avenue for
further exploration into other potential benets of data storytelling,
such as improved comprehension, which we explore next.
4.3 RQ2 - Data Storytelling and the Eective
Communication of Insights
When exploring whether data storytelling assisted the participants
in discerning and understanding critical data insights more eec-
tively compared to conventional visualisations, we discovered a
signicantly higher correct rate with moderate eect size for data
storytelling questions (median: 0.889, IQR: 0.333) than for conven-
tional data visualisation questions (median: 0.667, IQR: 0.334); U
= 3553, Z = 4.733, p < 0.0001, r = 0.33 (see Figure 5). This suggests
that incorporating data storytelling elements can enhance the ac-
curacy of responses to questions pertaining to key data points and
comprehension of insights when assessed across all tasks under-
taken by participants. While these results underscore the potential
CHI 24, May 1116, 2024, Honolulu, HI, USA Shao, et al.
Figure 4: Average success time (in seconds) of data storytelling versus conventional visualisations. The dierence was not
signicant.
for data storytelling to substantially improve the communication
of critical data points and insights, a more detailed analysis was
required, exploring variations in responses across dierent types
of questions including those concerning information retrieval
and the comprehension of single or multiple insights. The results
of further analysis are reported in the next section.
4.4 RQ3- Data Storytelling and Information
Retrieval and Comprehension Questions
In this section, we present a more detailed analysis concerning
the eciency and eectiveness of data storytelling in comparison
to conventional visualisations, taking into account the types of
questions posed (information retrieval and comprehension) as well
as the comprehension question sub-types (one insight and multiple
insights).
4.4.1 Eiciency and Information Retrieval and Comprehension. We
found that the average success time for information retrieval ques-
tions was actually higher when participants were presented with
data storytelling visualisations (median: 31.859 seconds, IQR: 21.166)
compared to conventional visualisations (median: 26.259 seconds,
IQR: 14.208) for information retrieval questions, but this dierence
was not signicant after p-value correction (U = 3517, Z = 2.229, p
= 0.1027, r = 0.155).
Contrary to this, although the average success time for com-

Z = -2.296, p = 0.0861, r = 0.16).
Separating the comprehension questions further into single in-

and this dierence was signicant following p-value correction
with a small eect size (U = 1192, Z = -2.686, p = 0.0283, r = 0.187).
Notwithstanding, data storytelling decreased the average success
time of single insight comprehension questions by an average of
4 seconds. We found that the average success time for multiple in-

storytelling (median: 43.812 seconds, IQR: 31.031) compared to
conventional visualisations (median: 49.232 seconds, IQR: 29.053);
however, this dierence was also not statistically signicant (U =
1285, Z = -1.378, p = 0.6757, r = 0.096).
In sum, conventional visualisations actually facilitated quicker
responses in information retrieval tasks compared to data story-
telling. Although data storytelling showed a trend towards reduced
success times in comprehension tasks, particularly for questions
targeting single insights, the dierences were not signicant.

4.5 RQ4 - Perceptions on the Helpfulness of
Data Storytelling Elements
We captured the participants perceptions about how Data Story-
telling (DS) elements contributed to eectiveness and eciency. All
the participants, but one out of 102, said that data storytelling ele-
ments were helpful for them to identify the ndings quickly. Colour
emphasis was regarded by more than half of the participants (68 out
of 102) as helpful in increasing their eciency in answering those
questions, as depicted in Figure 8. Textual elements, such as text
annotations (N=45), annotated data points (N=45) and explanatory
titles (N=45), were also perceived as contributing to identifying
relevant information in the data stories quickly. When asked which
elements actually helped them respond to the questions, about half
of the participants (N=52) indicated that text annotations were help-
ful, followed by annotated data points (N=46) and colour emphasis
(N=44) (see Figure 9).
Put together, these results suggest that the participants perceived
the colour emphasis as helpful to drive attention to the critical data
points of the data story, but the textual information in the form of
annotations was considered critical to gain an understanding of the
insights. Below, we elaborated on ve themes that emerged when
participants were asked to further explain their responses.
4.5.1 Theme 1 - Perceived DS usefulness to support data understand-
ing. The rst theme referred to the usefulness of data storytelling
visual elements to identify key information to support the un-
derstanding of the data and reduce complexity (N=24). Visual
elements like "added brief explanations" [textual annotations] (P15),
"colour schemes" [colour emphasis](P26, P29), and "clear labelling"
[annotated data points] (P27) helped participants to "identify the
important elements" on the graph more readily (P15, P18, P22).
The participants emphasised the role of textual elements, whether
annotations or explanatory titles, in making the data "easier to un-
derstand" (P66, P67). These storytelling elements were not merely
facilitative but often essential for understanding the graph: ("some
graphics are harder to interpret, and the text [annotations] helped
me to understand them [graphics] better" P49), as they "helped to
give facts rather than estimations" (P19, P36).
4.5.2 Theme 2 - More eicient interpretation of data. Another theme
that emerged referred to the perceived role of data storytelling
elements in enhancing their eciency when identifying key
information (N=26). For example, some participants explained
that these elements acted as guides that helped them "identify more
eciently the relevant information" (P60, P67, P68) and "[convey]
the main idea and the key points faster" (P67), sometimes even obvi-
ating the need for detailed chart analysis: "Without analysing the
chart I would get the information needed just by reading the textual
annotations" P61. This eciency could be attributed to the use of
data storytelling elements to focus their visual attention. Textual
elements combined with colour emphasis helped the participants
to "focus [their] attention" (P70) and nd answers "way quicker"

4.5.3 Theme 3 - Easier and more accurate interpretations of the data.
Participants
(N=21) also perceived that the storytelling elements en-

Colour emphasis and annotated data points were acknowledged
for their role in making data "easier to interpret" (P42, P43, P47)

noted that explanatory titles, textual annotations and colour em-
phasis made it "easier to locate information" (P26), enabling them to
answer questions with greater condence and accuracy ("with the
storytelling elements was easier nd the information to respond the
questions correctly" P24; "it made my interpretations more accurate"
P51). This was echoed by P16, who felt that such elements present
the information at a glance to "speed up the process" of reaching the
correct answer.
Similarly, textual annotations and annotated data points were
perceived as helpful to "reinforce the graphic information" (P41) and
"conrming assumptions" (P40), thereby allowing for more accurate
responses to questions. Interestingly, while some participants (P26,
P37) felt that they could have eventually gured out their responses
without these storytelling elements, they acknowledged that data
storytelling elements made the identication of key information
faster and more focused. This perspective was echoed by P41, who
felt that data storytelling "reinforces the graphic information and
helps to understand better and integrate any data that may not appear
immediate at rst analysis". These perspectives suggest that data
storytelling elements make the data interpretation process more
precise, allowing participants to validate their initial interpretations
and derive insights with greater condence.
4.5.4 Theme 4 - Negative perceptions and concerns. In contrast to
the perceived benets of data storytelling elements highlighted
above, some participants (N=16) found that these elements were
not always eective for interpreting data visualisations. Such
elements, particularly textual elements (i.e., annotated data points,
textual annotations and explanatory titles), could introduce confu-
sion ("actually made the data more confusing to look at" P85, "its
just a lot of information and it can be a bit overwhelming" P97) or
serve as distractions if not used eectively ("the highlights [textual
annotations] are kind of distracting from other data if done for only
one thing" P87, "the [textual annotations] distracted me from the
correct visualisation of the data." P100). Some participants (N=6)
also questioned the need for these visual elements, arguing that
the data was self-explanatory and that storytelling elements did
not add signicant value ("The data pretty much explains itself ...
the ones with data storytelling did not make that much dierence."
P86) or that the non-storytelling graph was "easier to interpret",
"clear" and "more visually appealing" (P88, P92, P98). Some par-
ticipants (N=3) expressed concerns about the potential for these
elements to be misleading or distracting. P90 elaborated on this
as follows: "I preferred to base my responses on graphs b ecause I
didnt know if the information about the visualisations [textual an-
notations] were true to the presented data", while another found
the highlights "distracting from the correct visualisation of the data"
(P100). These comments suggest that while data storytelling el-
ements could be benecial, these should be carefully crafted to
avoid information overload, particularly when the data is easier to
interpret.

5 DISCUSSION
In this section, we summarise the key ndings, share our critical
reections on the implications for research and practice, and note
the limitations of our study and potential avenues of future work.
5.1
Summary of Results and Research Questions
In Dykes [
24
] view, the purpose of a data story is to guide the
audience to a better understanding and appreciation of an impor-
tant data point or insight. Our study aimed to test whether data
storytelling can assist individuals in more eectively and eciently
discerning and understanding critical data points and insights com-
pared to conventional visualisations. We assessed the identication
of critical data points through information retrieval questions and
insight recognition through comprehension questions.
Regarding RQ1, contrary to prior assumptions [
81
,
100
102
], our
results demonstrated no evidence that data storytelling improved ef-
ciency (measured by the time taken to successfully complete tasks)
when evaluating both information retrieval and comprehension
questions collectively. Although the existing literature suggested
that data storytelling would enable more efcient identication of
insights, this assumption had not been empirically tested before our
study. In contrast, for RQ2, strong evidence emerged suggesting that
data storytelling improved eectiveness (correct response rate) in
aiding participants to more accurately comprehend insights derived
from data stories compared to conventional visualisations. This nd-
ing conrms earlier non-empirical assumptions [
37
,
50
] and the
foundational definition of data storytelling by Dykes [24].
Regarding RQ3, we found varied outcomes on data storytellings
eciency for dierent question types. Despite predictions grounded
in RQ1 outcomes, data storytelling expedited answers to single-
insight comprehension questions but not to multiple insights queries.
This might be attributed to the inherently greater complexity of
multi-insight questions, as highlighted in our preliminary analysis.
Thus, data storytelling seems particularly adept at enhancing the
rapid comprehension of visualisations conveying a single central
insight, aligning with existing literature that suggests that a data
story should focus on a core insight or call to action (Principles #1
& #5) [
4
,
24
,
54
,
69
,
85
]. However, despite the observed dierence
in response times between single and multiple insight questions,
our analysis revealed that data storytelling fostered more accu-
rate answers across all question types, including both information
retrieval and comprehension questions. This suggests that data
storytelling eectively directs viewers to critical data points and
insights within a visualisation, improving accuracy even for tasks
demanding identication of multiple data points, albeit taking a
longer time to complete.
Regarding RQ4, a signicant number of participants (N=26)
found data storytelling elements, especially coloured emphasis,
benecial in eciently pinpointing vital details in the graphs (Prin-
ciple #4). Furthermore, while a majority found some storytelling
elements benecial to some degree in eectively answering the ques-
tions (i.e., text annotations and annotated data points), a smaller
group (N=16) found them distracting and unhelpful, underlining
the importance of judicious use of these elements in accordance
with our third design principle discerning employment of story-
telling elements. This reects previous research suggesting that, for
some, these features might be more obstructive than facilitative
[
49
]. The feedback also hinted at a possible adverse eect of using
data storytelling for individuals procient in data analysis, with
some preferring conventional visualisations with detailed data over
textual annotations [46].
Regarding RQ5, we investigated how an individuals visualiza-
tion literacy impacts the ecacy of data storytelling. Our ndings
indicated a moderate to strong relationship between visualisation
literacy and the accuracy rates for both data storytelling and con-
ventional visualisation. Contrary to popular belief upheld in prior
studies [
31
,
60
,
102
], our results did not statistically arm that
data storytelling is more benecial for individuals with lower visu-
alisation literacy. This implies that data storytelling is uniformly
advantageous for users, regardless of their visualisation literacy
level.
In summary, based on our results, we provide the following sug-
gestions to design practitioners interested in using data storytelling
elements for communicating insights:
(1)
Data stories can be more effective compared to conventional
visualisation in communicating insights, although the data
stories may not necessarily help in nding the insights faster
(RQ1 & RQ2).
(2)
Data stories may be more efcient compared to conventional
visualisations for tasks that involve identifying a single in-
sight but not necessarily for searching specic data points or
identifying multiple/complex insights from a visualisation.
(RQ3)
(3)
For information retrieval tasks, especially for users with
strong analysis expertise, it may be preferable to reconsider
the need for adding data storytelling elements to conven-
tional visualisations. (RQ4)
(4)
Excessive addition of data storytelling elements, particularly
those that are text-based, may hinder simple data tasks or
be distracting for certain users. (RQ4)
(5)
Data stories aid in the effective identication of insights rel-
atively equally for all users, regardless of their data literacy
levels. (RQ5)
(6)
At the same time, a higher level of data literacy in a user
may lead to more effective identication of insights, whether
using a data story or a conventional visualisation. (RQ5)
5.2 Implications for Research
While previous research has yielded mixed results regarding the
benets of data storytelling in areas such as engagement [
10
,
103
],
empathy [
11
,
58
,
64
], and memory recall [
99
], our study supports
the fundamental notion that data storytelling is an effective medium
for conveying insights. Our ndings add to this body of work by
demonstrating that data storytelling not only effectively aids in iden-
tifying insights but also does so more efciently when pinpointing
a single insight within a visualisation. However, this effectiveness
and efciency in insight identication does not necessarily enhance
memory recall, as previously suggested by Zdanovic et al
. [99]
.
Moreover, even if the insights can be identied more effectively,
adding annotations and other storytelling elements to conventional
visualisations may not always increase engagement [
10
,
103
] or
empathy towards the subject matter [
11
,
58
,
64
]. Our results did
CHI 24, May 1116, 2024, Honolulu, HI, USA Shao, et al.
not directly contradict earlier negative studies, as these did not
measure the effectiveness and efciency of data storytelling in in-
formation retrieval and comprehension of insights. Consequently,
our study represents an initial step in a broader research agenda,
advocating for more comprehensive investigations into the role
and limits of data storytelling, a tool increasingly prevalent across
various sectors [70, 83, 90, 97].
Our results resonate with the notion posited by Dykes
[24]
and
others, portraying data storytelling as an eective tool in conveying
insights [
20
,
37
,
47
,
51
,
85
]. Our results hold substantial implications
for research, highlighting the key role data storytelling can play in
amplifying data comprehension and communication. Researchers in
elds such as data science, journalism, and education can potentially
explore how to adopt its foundational design principles for broader
audience engagement [9, 55].
Moreover, they underpin the necessity for further studies to
delve into the optimal ways of employing data storytelling ele-
ments, as several dierent variations of data storytelling exist [
4
],
aiming not just for clarity and eectiveness of insight communi-
cation but also fostering a deeper connection with the audience.
Furthermore, the critical feedback received in our study signals
a pathway for investigating the potential downsides of data sto-
rytelling, for example, considering the ethical considerations of
emphasising certain stories over others, which has started to be
explored by Fernandez-Nieto et al. [29].
Moreover, our research also sheds new light regarding the suit-
ability of data storytelling to particularly support general audiences
with limited data visualisation expertise, presenting a dierent pic-
ture compared to the ndings of Pozdniakov et al
. [73]
. Despite
their smaller study highlighting a reduced cognitive load among 23
teachers through the use of basic data storytelling elements, we did
not nd a direct link between visualisation literacy and data story-
telling eectiveness. However, we noted that visualisation literacy
did aect the ability to discern insights in both conventional visual-
isations and data stories. This opens avenues for deeper exploration
into the intricate relationship between visualisation literacy and
data storytelling, encouraging a broader understanding of the role
visualisation literacy plays in the realm of data visualisation.
5.3 Implications for Practice
This study validates emerging guidelines for practitioners in various
industries, conrming the potential of data storytelling to enhance
information retrieval and comprehension tasks [28, 47, 82]. It also
illustrates that data storytelling can be a vital tool for marketing
campaigns and educational purposes, where precise data compre-
hension is paramount, proving especially ecient for single-insight
tasks [
24
,
62
,
86
,
93
]. The proven eectiveness (and eciency for
single insight tasks) can be invaluable in decision-making contexts,
highlighting its role in facilitating both timely and accurate inter-
pretation of data representations [20, 83].
Interestingly, we observed a slightly prolonged response time in
the data storytelling condition for information retrieval questions,
although the dierence was not signicant. This nding prompts
a cautionary note for designers to avoid overloading data stories
with excessive elements such as too detailed annotation texts and
lengthy explanatory titles, which can potentially hinder simple
tasks [28, 47, 82, 92]. Thus, presenters must judiciously determine
the cognitive demands of their tasks and tailor their use of data
storytelling to meet those [4, 24, 54, 85].
Our study underscored that data storytelling aids users of all
visualisation literacy levels equally, hinting at its potential util-
ity compared to conventional data visualisations, especially for
the general public. This approach, already adopted successfully
by newspapers, could potentially revolutionise the way research
ndings are communicated through scientic visualisations, mak-
ing them more accessible to the public [
60
,
69
]. Leveraging data
storytelling in places like museums and scientic events could en-
hance the comprehension of the complex data being presented,
encouraging a deeper understanding [17].
Looking ahead, there exists a promising avenue for creating
automated or AI tools to seamlessly blend data storytelling ele-
ments into data visualisations, a frontier with considerable room
for growth, despite existing progress in automatic annotation cre-
ation [29, 52, 57, 96].
5.4 Limitations and Future Work
Our study has several acknowledged limitations in terms of the
data collection and the study design decisions. Regarding data
collection, the participant pool, constrained by the recruitment plat-
form and available resources, lacked ideal diversity with an over-
representation from the Americas and an under-representation of
other regions. Moreover, we restricted our exploration to six pairs
of visualisations, limiting the breadth of data storytelling elements
and visualisation types assessed. Future research should aim to
involve a broader, more diverse participant group and extend the
range of visualisations studied to foster a more comprehensive
analysis [56, 71].
Moreover, the study was conducted exclusively in English, and
while participants were required to be procient in English, their
perceived prociency levels were not documented. Given that data
storytelling substantially emphasises narrative which can in-
herently vary across languages our results might not hold the
same ground in dierent linguistic contexts [
71
]. Therefore, further
work is recommended to reproduce this study in other languages.
Additionally, the online format of the study potentially encour-
aged hurried participation due to the xed monetary compensation.
Moreover, concurrent distractions could have further diluted partic-
ipants focus. Future endeavours could look to include deeper qual-
itative analysis through oine methodologies such as interviews
to avoid these issues. In the same vein, we summarised the overall
perceptions of data storytelling elements in terms of their effective-
ness and efciency in identifying insights, based on responses to
questions. Future studies could utilise eye-tracking technology to
investigate how each data storytelling element contributes to the
efciency and effectiveness of retrieval or comprehension tasks,
similar to smaller-scale studies like those in [26] and [72].
Regarding the study design, we tailored the visualisation literacy
test (VLAT) to focus specically on the visualisations central to
our study, sidelining other pertinent techniques featured in the
complete VLAT [
56
]. This strategy, while facilitating the study exe-
cution, highlights the necessity for future research to investigate
the visualisation techniques that were not considered in our study.

Moreover, the scope of our inquiry centred predominantly on the
initial two levels of Blooms taxonomy, limiting the study to evalu-
ating data storytellings aid in key data points retrieval and insights
comprehension. Subsequent studies can delve into higher tiers of
the taxonomy to evaluate aspects such as data story manipulation
and the creation of personal data stories [2, 15, 16, 63].
Additionally, our study design considered changes in the type of
charts when transforming from conventional visualisations to data
stories, adhering to recommendations from the literature [
47
,
99
].
The results revealed no significant differences when changing the
type of chart. Yet, further studies may consider a deeper

by considering the participants spatial skills [

].
Moreover, al-
though we followed design guidelines by Zdanovic
et al
. [99]
and
Knaflic

to transform conventional
visualisations into data sto-

performed by three researchers, external expert validation can
be recommended to provide addi-tional credibility to the data
storytelling construction process. Lastly, we limited our
investigation to static data storytelling to
maintain study
simplicity, excluding interactive elements that can
enrich data
narratives. Future work can benefit significantly from
exploring
interactive patterns in data storytelling to enhance user
engagement [4].
5.5 Conclusion
As society grapples with the overwhelming volume of data gen-
erated every moment, data storytelling emerges as a potent tool
promising to distill complex data into discernible insights, thereby
facilitating informed decision-making. Our research shows that
data storytelling can be a way to identify key data points and in-
sights more accurately and effectively, even though it might not
always be faster than using conventional visualisations. We also
noticed that being skilled at understanding visualisations is key
to getting the most out of them, but data storytelling is helpful
for people at all visualisation literacy levels. We argue, supported
by our study, that this work advances the state of the art in un-
derstanding the benefits of data storytelling for the retrieval and
comprehension of key data points and insights hidden in large sets.
